{{Semiotics}}
'''Zoosemiotics''' is the [[semiotic]] study of the use of signs among animals, more precisely the study of [[semiosis]] among animals, i.e. the study of how something comes to function as a sign to some animal.<ref>[[Timo Maran|Maran, Timo]]; [[Dario Martinelli|Martinelli, Dario]]; [[Aleksei Turovski|Turovski, Aleksei]] (eds.), 2011. ''Readings in Zoosemiotics.'' ([[Semiotics, Communication and Cognition]] 8.). Berlin: De Gruyter Mouton.</ref> It is the study of animal forms of knowing.<ref>[[Kalevi Kull|Kull, Kalevi]] 2014. Zoosemiotics is the study of animal forms of knowing. ''Semiotica'' 198: 47–60.[https://www.academia.edu/6116777/Zoosemiotics_is_the_study_of_animal_forms_of_knowing]</ref>

Considered part of [[biosemiotics]], zoosemiotics is related to the fields of [[ethology]] and [[animal communication]].<ref>Witzany, Guenther. 2014. Biocommunication of Animals. Dortrecht, Springer. </ref> It was developed by semiotician [[Thomas Sebeok]] based on the theories of German-Estonian biologist [[Jakob von Uexküll]].<ref>"Zoosemiotics". [[Thomas A. Sebeok]]. American Speech , Vol. 43, No. 2 (May, 1968), pp. 142-144</ref><ref>Zoosemiotics: Juncture of Semiotics and the Biological Study of Behavior. Science 29 January 1965:  Vol. 147 no. 3657 pp. 492-493</ref> The field is defined by having as its subject matter all of those semiotic processes that are shared by both animals and humans.<ref>Baer, Eugen. 1987. Thomas A. Sebeok's Doctrine of Signs, in Krampen, et al. (eds.) "Classics of Semiotics" Plenum Press. p. 187</ref> The field also differs from the field of animal communication in that it also interprets signs that are not communicative in the traditional sense, such as camouflage, [[mimicry]], courtship behavior etc. The field also studies cross-species communication, for example between humans and animals.<ref>[http://www.semioticon.com/seo/Z/zoosemiotics.html Martinelli, Dario. "Zoosemiotics" in Semiotics Encyclopedia Online. E.J. Pratt Library - Victoria University.]</ref>

